    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.16.19"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">19</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="italic">Charles <hi rend="caps">F.</hi> Haanel</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    113-115 <hi rend="caps">LOCUST STREET
                        <lb/>
                ST. LOUIS, MO.</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>February 26th, 1934.</dateline>
                    
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt;--</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>The first thing that I do every Sunday Morning, after breakfast, is to unfold the Post-Dispatch, turn to the Editorial page and see what you have to say about the most recent books - and I am never disappointed, because you always have something interesting to say, and I am always in sympathy with your comment.</p>
                
                <p>I noticed that yesterday you said that "Even though prayer may be no more than a passionate appeal to the deeper self of the suppliant", may not that "deeper self" be the "Life Principle" and may it not be a part in the same <del/><add>"</add>Principle" in every one, if so may it not be what men have chosen to call "God".</p>
                
                <p>If so, may this not be the explanation, not only of the answer to prayer, but also to much of the occult phenomena, which seems so unusual and in some cases startling.</p>
                
                <p>I have written a treatise on this subject which I call the Master Key, and am taking the librerty of sending you a copy of the first British Edition.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very truly,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Charles F. Haanel</signed>
                
                    <note>CFH:EP</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
